erleden","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1420–1500":"1420–1500","before 1464":"vóór 1464","1440":"1440","1561":"1561","1483":"1483","1461":"1461","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1500":"1500","1464":"1464","1486":"1486","1420":"1420","1505":"1505","1527":"1527","1516":"1516","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England":"Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England","Weston, Cheshire, England":"Weston, Cheshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England",", , , England":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1464–1490":"1464–1490","1461–1516":"1461–1516","1480–1561":"1480–1561","1486–1527":"1486–1527","1505–Female":"1505–Deceased","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1420–1500":"1420–1500","before 1464":"before 1464","1440":"1440","1561":"1561","1483":"1483","1461":"1461","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1500":"1500","1464":"1464","1486":"1486","1420":"1420","1505":"1505","1527":"1527","1516":"1516","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England":"Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England","Weston, Cheshire, England":"Weston, Cheshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England",", , , England":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fowke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name  <i>Folk</i>,  <i>Fulk</i>,  <i>Fuke</i>.  Compare  Foxon  . For a variant form of the personal name  see  Foulkes  .  See also  Fudge  , which may sometimes be a variant form."],"variants":[{"name":"Fudge","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English, Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulch</i> or <i>Fuche</i>, usually a pet form of Old French <i>Fulcher</i>, <i>Fucher</i> (see   Fulcher  ). Voicing of ‘ch’ to soft ‘g’ gave rise to <i>Fudge</i>. The name may sometimes have been interchangeable with <b>Fowke</b> (for which see   Foulk   1), derived from a pet form of this and other Old French personal names in <i>Fulc-</i>.","English: habitational name from Fuge, in Blackawton, Devon. This placename is composed of Old English <i>feoh</i> ‘cattle’ + <i>wīc</i> ‘farm, dairy farm, village’."]},{"name":"Folke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Fook","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke  ."]},{"name":"Foulk","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Middle English and Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Fulk</i>, which is of ancient Germanic origin, ultimately from an element meaning ‘folk, people’."]},{"name":"Fogg","meanings":["English (northern): possibly a variant of <b>Fowke</b> (see   Foulk   1). It may derive from Middle English <i>fogge</i> ‘aftermath’ (i.e. grass left to grow after the hay has been cut, also applied to long grass in a water meadow), especially in northern England, where the term occurs as a specifying element in minor placenames, but as it is not found on its own as a simplex name, the derivation is doubtful without some supporting evidence. The word <i>fogge</i>, which is probably of Old Norse origin, is still in use as a dialect term in Craven, Yorkshire, and in eastern Lancashire. modern English <i>fog</i> ‘thick mist’ is first attested in the 16th century and is unlikely to be the source of the surname."]},{"name":"Fuke","meanings":["Norman, English:  see  Fowke   and  compare  Fook  ."]},{"name":"Folk","meanings":["German: variant of   Volk   1 and, in North America, also an altered form of this. This form of the surname is also found in Czechia.","English: variant of   Foulk   1."]},{"name":"Focke","meanings":["North German, East Frisian, and Dutch: from the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Folco</i>, a pet form of various names beginning with <i>Folc-</i> or <i>Volk-</i>; cognate with   Foulk   1.","English (of Norman origin): variant of   Foulk   1. See also   Foulks  ."]},{"name":"Foulke","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Shropshire): variant of   Foulk  ."]},{"name":"Fulk","meanings":["English: variant of   Foulk   1.","Altered form of German   Volk   or   Falk  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Fowke was born in 1464, in Brewood, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, William Fowke, was 25 and her mother, Margaret Legh, was 45. She had at least 1 son and 2 daughters with John Whorwood. She died in 1490, in Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1464–1490":"1464–1490","1461–1516":"1461–1516","1480–1561":"1480–1561","1486–1527":"1486–1527","1505–Female":"1505–Surnud","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1420–1500":"1420–1500","before 1464":"enne 1464","1440":"1440","1561":"1561","1483":"1483","1461":"1461","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1500":"1500","1464":"1464","1486":"1486","1420":"1420","1505":"1505","1527":"1527","1516":"1516","Brewood, Staffordshire, England":"Brewood, Staffordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England":"Wolverhampton, Staffordshire, England","Weston, Cheshire, England":"Weston, Cheshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England",", , , England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1464–1490":"1464–1490","1461–1516":"1461–1516","1480–1561":"1480–1561","1486–1527":"1486–1527","1505–Female":"1505–Kuollut","1440–1483":"1440–1483","1420–1500":"1420–1500","before 1464":"ennen vuotta 1464","1440":"1440","1561":"1561","1483":"1483","1461":"1461","1480":"1480","1490":"1490","1500":"1500","1464":"1464","1486":"1486","1420":"1420","1505":"1505","1527":"1527","1516":"1516","Brew